<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Tsuga</i> <i>mertensiana</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Abies</i> <i>concolor</i>, <i>Abies</i> <i>magnifica</i>, <i>Abies</i> <i>procera</i>, <i>Abies</i> Ã—<i>shastensis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>albicaulis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i> and <i>Pinus</i> <i>monticola</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 40 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Shrub layer is sparse to abundant. Herbaceous layer is sparse to abundant. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Tsuga mertensiana</i> > 60% relative cover or > 25% relative cover in the tree canopy in mixed stands (Nature-Serve 2007a).</li>
		
		<li><i>Tsuga mertensiana</i> is a co-dominant with <i>A. magnifica, P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana,</i> or <i>P. monticola;</i> and <i>P. albicaulis</i> has insignificant cover in the tree canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Subalpine stream benches, slopes, most extensive on north-facing aspects and lake margins. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Tsuga mertensiana</i> as a FACU+ plant. </div>
</div>

        
