<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Tsuga mertensiana </i>is not well adapted to fire because it has relatively thin bark, low-hanging branches, and flammable foliage. Stands occur in areas with long fire return intervals where fuel loading is often low. When fires do occur, they are often severe and stand-replacing (Sugihara et al. 2006). Surviving trees with fire injury are susceptible to disease and insects, such as the laminated root rot (<i>Phellinus weiri</i>) and Indian paint fungus (<i>Echinodontium tinctorum;</i><i> </i>Means 1990, Tesky 1992f ).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
