    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ad, Ag, Aj, An-o, As). Stands are common at subalpine elevations on glaciated slopes leading up to sectionâ€™s highest mountain tops and ridges at Cedar Basin rRNA, Crater Creek cRNA, and Sugar Creek cRNA (Cheng 2004), at Diamond Lake (Sawyer and Thornburgh 1969), and regionally in the section (Jimerson 1993, Sawyer 2007, Sawyer and Thornburgh 1977).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dl). Stands occur east of the Sierra crest in the Mammoth region.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). A small stand between Black Rock Mountain and North Yolla Bolly Mountain is the only one in the section. However, some authors consider this part of the Klamath Mountains (M261A).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ed-e, Eh, Ej-k, En-o, Eq-r, Et). Stands are common and extensive at subalpine elevations at Harvey Monroe Hall and Lyon Peak/Needle Peak RNAs (Cheng 2004), in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), and regionally in the northern and central subsections (Parsons 1972, Potter 1998, Rundel et al. 1977). Many stands have few shrubs or herbs. The species is found as individuals or small, isolated groves at its southern</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Df, Di, Dm). Stands are common and extensive at subalpine elevations on all the major volcanic peaks, where they sometimes form timberline at Antelope Creek Lakes cRNA and Red Butte-Red Fir RNA (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Many stands exist in designed wilderness. Those elsewhere may be candidates for logging on sites with large trees, but sites at these elevations are inherently unproductive. Trees may be sensitive to climatic change, especially in the southern range of the species. </div>
</div>

    

    

